['As per the calculation of the total volume for each proposal, which is the product of the proposed outcome raised to the (normalized) group size for each group, the proposals two and three both have the maximum total volume. However, the best compromise would take into consideration the interest of all the groups and distribute the benefits more evenly across them. 

Proposal one only heavily favors group "cow-üêÆ", leaving "apple-üçé" and "bee-üêù" with very little increase in the outcome. 

On the other hand, proposal two and three both favor two groups, "apple-üçé" and "bee-üêù", and "bee-üêù" and "cow-üêÆ" respectively, with significant outcome improvements and give a reasonable improvement for one group. 

Given this, it appears that proposal two and three both are a better compromise as they provide significant outcomes to two groups instead of one in proposal one.

However, I am only allowed to choose one proposal. Since both proposals two and three increase the benefits of two groups quite significantly, I will choose the one that causes the least disparity between the most and the least benefitted groups. 

Proposal two has an improvement of 101 days for group "apple-üçé" and 1 day for group "cow-üêÆ" - a difference of 100 days. 

While proposal three has a difference of 100 days as well between group "bee-üêù" and "apple-üçé", the group "cow-üêÆ" that was the most benefitted in proposal one is still quite significantly benefitted in proposal three with a reduction of 51 days in waiting time, as compared to just 1 day for group "cow-üêÆ" in proposal two. 

Therefore, considering that all three groups get a significant outcome improvement across proposals one to three, proposal three (C) seems to spread the benefits more evenly across all groups when taking the three proposals collectively into consideration. 

Hence, my answer is (C) Proposal three.

['Given that proposals two and three provide a significantly greater benefit for group bee-üêù while only decreasing the benefit for the other groups minimally, a good compromise would be either of these proposals. Since they are identical, we can randomly pick one. Therefore, the answer is (B) Proposal two.
B', "Let's think about compromise. In a compromise, all groups should gain something and no group should be left completely unsatisfied. Looking at the proposals, they differ only in the relief they provide to group bee. All other groups get exactly the same relief in each proposal. Still, the relief varies for group bee in the other two proposals.

Proposal one offers an equal relief of 1.0 dollars to all three groups. This is fair in some sense, but group bee-üêù could get much more relief in the other proposals. 

Proposal two and three give a significant boost to group bee-üêù without any loss to the other groups.

All groups gain something in all of the proposals but proposals two and three offer extra relief to group bee-üêù.

Since both proposal two and three are the same, either of them would serve as the best compromise in this situation.

So, the answer could be (B) Proposal two or (C) Proposal three. But since the demand of the task is to give exactly one answer, let's choose (B) Proposal two. However, keep in mind that proposal three would serve equally well.
